	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f104739845644143><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=item.html?item=313&mid=104739845644143>RE: help</a> <a id=fs8 href=item.html?item=313&mid=104739845644143#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=86947><span id=Guru>Annheiser</span></a>, <span id=Guru>Guru</span><br><span id=notbold>170 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Tue, Mar 11th 11:34 AM 2003</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Both of my examples <b>are</b> for group situations. If you're soloing, I'd advise going for the pure damage as you can always back off and DoT and heal (assuming you've snared and such).<br><br>Stats are pretty damn trivial when you're looking at weapons. The first and foremost thing to look at is the delay. After that, you look at the AC bonuses it could give or HP, and then you look at the proc if there is one. For your off-hand, you look at ratio. It doesn't matter if a shoddy weapon gives you 20 DEX and STR. The effects of stats are marginal at best, and you should never, ever base your decision of a weapon on stat bonuses.<br><br>When you fight as a Ranger, you look for Damage first, and then AC and HP second (again assuming you are grouping with incompetant tanks that can not taunt better than you).<br>&nbsp;<br>**********************************<br>"<span style='color: red;'>Man who goes to bed with itchy bum, wakes with smelly fingers.</span style='color: red;'>"</td></tr>
